         <abstract>
            <p>The hypotenuse function, z = &lt;tex-math&gt;$\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}$&lt;/tex-math&gt;, is sometimes included in math library packages. Assuming that it is being computed by a straight-forward algorithm, in a binary floating point environment, with round to nearest rounding mode, a sharp roundoff error bound is derived, for arbitrary precision. For IEEE single precision, or higher, the bound implies that &lt;latex&gt;$\mid\overline{z} - z\mid &lt; 1.222 ulp(z)$&lt;/latex&gt; and &lt;latex&gt;$\mid\overline {z} - z\mid &lt; 1.222 ulp(\overline{z})$&lt;/latex&gt;. Numerical experiments indicate that this bound is sharp and cannot be improved.</p>
          </abstract>
